==Norwegian Bokmål==
{{wikipedia|lang=no}}

===Etymology===
Directly borrowed from {{bor|no|el|Ελλάς||Greece}}, possibly being influenced by {{bor|no|grc|Ἑλλάς||Greece}}, in 1932 to replace the Danish loanword and German cognate {{l|no|Grekenland}} as part of a trend to adopt [[endonym]]s as Norway was nation-building during the early 20th century and as a compromise during the early stages of the {{w|Norwegian language conflict}}, with [[Nynorsk]] and [[Samnorsk]] advocates rejecting the existing name and ''Grekerland'', a calque of Swedish {{l|sv|Grekland}}, only working in [[Bokmål]] (where {{l|en|Greek}} is {{l|no|greker}}, being {{l|no|grekar}} instead in Nynorsk). In the 1970s, the Norwegian Foreign Ministry attempted to reverse the name change to be more similar to other European countries. Although this movement gained enough momentum to make it to the {{w|Language Council of Norway}}, it was rejected by a majority of the Council.<ref>{{cite-journal|author=|authorlink=|title=Lesarspørsmål|url=https://www.sprakradet.no/Vi-og-vart/Publikasjoner/Spraaknytt/spraknytt-20162/spraknytt-12016/lesarsporsmal/#hellas|archiveurl=|archivedate=|journal=Språknytt|location=Oslo|publisher={{w|Language Council of Norway|Language Council of Norway (Språkrådet)}}|date=January 2016|volume=|issue=|page=|pages=3-4|pageurl=|issn=0333-3825|oclc=|text=}} ([https://www.sprakradet.no/globalassets/vi-og-vart/publikasjoner/spraknytt/2016/12016/spraknytt-1-2016.pdf?id=10924 PDF])</ref>

